Judge's Verdict for CFJ 1073:

Judge's reasoning and Arguments:

The central question of the Statement, once it is given that there were 
unequivocally posts to the PF that alleged themselves to be player's 
votes on the given proposals, is whether or not the infection of Rule 
1598 prevented those votes from being, in the terms of Rule 206, Rule 
683, Rule 1741 and others, "cast."

Looking at what the infection of Rule 1598 did to the Ruleset, it left 
the Rules without an explicit definition of what a Transfer Order was, 
and more importantly it left us without a definition of what it was to 
submit or execute a Transfer Order.  While it might have been legal for 
Recordkeepors to continue paying attention to attempted TOs without 
these definitions, the fact is they did not do so, and that decision was 
at least as legal as the alternative.  So it is a fact that no TOs were 
successfully made or executed during the period of Rule 1598.

So the question is, can a Vote be cast without a successful Transfer 
Order?  Can Votes be cast when TOs are prevented by the Rules?

Rule 1442 [Power 1] states;

     "The casting of any votes may only be achieved by the spending of 
      VTs, as specified below. . ."

The term "spending" is a unique term, that I find only in this Rule, and 
nowhere else in all the technical jargon of our Currency Rules.  If the 
word was not used as it is, I would argue for the common-sense 
definition of the term re Currencies, but the Rule does not allow this, 
since it specifies, "as specified below."  The Rule defines its own 
meaning for "spending a VT."

Rule 1442 [cont.]

     "A Voting Entity Votes upon a Proposal when e, during the Voting
      Period of that Proposal, informs the Assessor of the Vote (or
      Votes) e is casting upon that Proposal.  This act also comprises
      the implicit submission of a delayed Transfer Order from the
      Voting Entity to the Bank for however many VTs are necessary to
      cast those Votes, to be executed at the end of the Voting Period
      of that Proposal, and also the implicit cancellation of all
      other delayed Transfer Orders submitted but not yet executed by
      Voting on that Proposal."

>From the way this is worded, the only adequate definition for "spending 
a VT" we can glean from this rule is the "implicit submission of a 
delayed Transfer Order [...] for however many VTs."   If a player can 
only cast a Vote by spending VTs, the above paragraph states how those 
votes are cast (a message to the Assessor) and how the VTs are spent (an 
implied delayed Transfer Order.)

This is further strengthened by the wording later on where;

Rule 1442 [cont.]

     "A Voting Entity may specify that e casts no Votes on a Proposal,
      and doing so cancels any previously Votes cast on that Proposal
      (if done during the Voting Period of that Proposal) and cancels
      any delayed Transfer Orders submitted but not yet executed by
      Voting on that Proposal."

The fact that when a vote is "uncast", the TO goes away implies that the
 implied TO is the "spending" and _not_ the implied TO's execution.  
This is important, since during the infection of 1598 we had no 
mechanism for successfully executing TOs, that didn't mean that Votes 
did not continue to create implied TOs.  What the infection did was make 
"implied TO" a noun without context or effect, but not without 
existence.  (Essentially rendering the 1442 the same as if all instances 
of delayed Transfer Orders with the word Blorg.  We don't know what a 
Blorg is, or what it does, but 1442 more or less equates creating a 
Blorg with spending a VT, which is its requirement for casting a vote.)

----

Side Note: Rule 1730 is a strange bird which gives a stopgap
interpretation for Delayed Transfer Order.  It still fails to give a 
procedure for executing a TO, so it doesn't really affect the above 
interpretation.  But the first paragraph of 1730 is very strange;

1730 [Power 1]

     "If the Executor of the source entity specifies a later time
      (possibly implicitly) at which the Order is to be executed, then
      the Order is executed at that time, unless cancelled prior to
      that time.  An order of this latter type is called a "delayed
      Transfer Order."

It seems that it's lucky that Recordkeepors could still reject orders
during the infection, otherwise they might have found themselves under 
all sorts of uncomfortable obligations.  (Since IMO the capitalization 
of the word Order doesn't deprive it of its natural meaning in absence 
of a rule to the contrary.)

---

Back to Rule 1442 [cont.]

     "A Voting Entity's Votes on a given Proposal are counted for that
      Proposal only if the delayed Transfer Order implicitly submitted
      by Voting on that Proposal is successfully executed at the end
      of the Voting Period of that Proposal."

Setting aside the timing issue (if the Assessor delays the execution of 
TOs until a few hours after the end of the VP, the Rule implies they did 
not count) this is the crux of 1442 impact on the given Statement.  This 
is again because of the fact we have no executed TOs for the Proposals 
in question.  However, the problem is twofold;

  i) Can 1442 prevent Votes from being "counted"?
     (in the terms of Rule 955)
 ii) Would this prevent those Votes from being cast?

Last question first.  Rule 1442 already defines what it is to "cast" a 
vote, and it does not contradict that in the final paragraph.  According 
to 1442, a Vote is cast by sending a message to the Assessor and can 
only be "un-cast" by a cancellation of the Vote.  Whatever other rules 
say about "casting Votes" or even "casting VTs" the answer of whether 
1442 prevents casting Votes is fairly clear, it does not.

Now to the final question--
Does 1442 prevent Votes from being counted?

>From Rule 955 [Power 3]

     "When the Voting Period for a Proposal has ended, the Votes which
      have been legally cast shall be counted by the Assessor."

This trumps whatever 1442 would say to the contrary.  There has been 
some argument that the final restriction of 1442 implies that such Votes 
(without successfully executed TOs) are not "legally cast,"  but I think 
it is a stretch to avoid this conflict in that manner.  1442 implies 
nothing in its text about the legality of the casting of any Vote.  It 
merely defines what casting a Vote is, and makes an attempt at a 
restriction based on the results of that Vote (the implied TO).  It is 
transparent in the wording that Votes are cast at the time they are 
sent, and it is a strain to interpret the last paragraph of 1442 as 
retroactively illegalizing the casting of votes when it says nothing
about the casting of those Votes, but only about TOs and counting Votes.

It is this Judge's opinion that 1442 states that Votes are [legally] 
cast when the Voting Entity sends a message to the Assessor.  It is also 
the Judge's opinion that, due to the precedence of Rule 955, these Votes 
are to be counted by the Assessor regardless of the success or failure 
of any related Transfer Orders.  I hereby Judge the Statement True.
=========================
Evidence:



Rule 955/3 (Power=3)
Votes Required to Adopt a Proposal

      When the Voting Period for a Proposal has ended, the Votes which
      have been legally cast shall be counted by the Assessor.  The
      Proposal shall then be assigned a Voting Index, as follows: the
      Proposal received no Votes opposed, and at least one Vote in
      favor, the Voting Index shall be Unanimity; if there are no
      Votes in favor, the Voting Index shall be zero; in all other
      cases, the Voting Index shall be the number of Votes in favor
      divided by the number of Votes opposed.

      If the Voting Index is greater than the Adoption Index for the
      given Proposal, or if both equal Unanimity, then that Proposal
      passes.  Otherwise, it fails.

